Here is my pre-workout mobility routine that I had posted on my story a couple of weeks ago. A bunch of you guys wanted me to make it a permanent post so that you can refer to it in the future so here you go!
-
I am not a mobility expert by any means. As you can see, I don’t actually know the names of any of these movements. As I got older, I noticed I that I needed to warm up more and more prior to my workouts to feel ready and started incorporating some movements that I found helpful. I’m not trying to be a yoga expert. I’m just trying to loosen myself up to avoid injury and this has certainly helped me with that.
-
Feel free to give some of these a shot as well as others that you find work well for you. Depending on the areas that are tight for you, there may be some other exercises you want to include. Conversely, you may be able to skip some of the ones I do if you don’t find it helpful for you.
-
If you are struggling with 𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐜𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 your 𝐦𝐚𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐬, setting up 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐝𝐢𝐞𝐭, and designing an 𝐞𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞, check out my 𝐞𝐛𝐨𝐨𝐤 by clicking the 𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐦𝐲 𝐛𝐢𝐨💪🏼.
-
If you’re interested in working with me 1 on 1 for a custom plan tailored to your goals, send me an email for more information on online coaching.

Here is my most recent pull hypertrophy workout that I posted on my story a few days ago as I was doing it. For those of you who didn’t know, I always post my workouts on my story as I do them.
-
This is my second of two pull workouts for the week. The first one is with heavier weight and fewer reps. I posted that one a couple of weeks ago. My second one is with less weight and more reps.

Today’s workout was:

Lat Pulldowns: 4 sets of 10-12
One Arm Machine Rows: 4 sets of 10
Chest Supported Tbar Rows: 3 sets of 12-15
Rear Delt Flyes: 3 sets of 12
Hammer Curls: 3 sets of 20-25

Dumbbell Lateral Raises: 3 sets of 10

Calves are one of the toughest body parts to develop. Part of the reason is they are fairly dependent on your genetics (to a higher degree than most muscles in my opinion) and they also get trained incorrectly. I'd like to think I have pretty decent calves so I'll share 3 tips on what has helped me the most. Number 3 is the most crucial and is what I will discuss in this video.
-
1. Frequency: Train your calves at least 2-3 times per week with 4-8 sets each workout. You can even do calves at the end of every single workout. Your calves are used to a heavy workload since you've been walking on them your whole life. They can handle the work and you won't be overtraining them.
-
2. Form: Make sure you are actually using your calves when you do calf raises. Slow and controlled on the way down and pause for a second at the top. No bouncing or using momentum. Your calves are a small muscle and it's very easy to cheat and take the emphasis off them by letting your ego get in the way. People care about how much you bench, not how much you calf raise.
-
3. **Huge Drop Sets**: This is the single technique that has helped my calves the most. On your last set of calf raises, choose a weight you can hit for 8-12 reps. Do a drop set and on the drop set count 3 second negatives and pause for a second at the top of each rep. Go to failure and then do another drop set doing the same thing. Do 3 or 4 of these drop sets with the 3 second negatives and 1 second pause at the top with each set to failure. The set should take 2-4 minutes, your calves will be burning, and it will be the sickest pump you've ever gotten. Do this at least twice per week and your calves will grow.

CHEST BLAST by @apfau
-
I find that most people struggle to develop their upper chest compared to their lower chest. For that reason, I usually recommend focusing more on incline presses (or decline push-ups if you’re working out at home) to target the upper chest rather than exercises for your lower chest. However, if you’re one of the few who actually has a dominant upper chest and weak lower chest, weighted dips and decline bench should help. Either way, you should also be incorporating some flat bench as well.
-
A lot of people also want to target their inner chest. Unfortunately, you cannot specifically target it. (In before angry comments because I said you can’t target your inner chest).
-
The chest does not have different heads like triceps, biceps or shoulders which can be isolated. The fibers of the chest run horizontally and the entire chest contracts together. You can still emphasize the upper/lower regions as discussed above by varying your bench press angles but regardless of the angle you use, your entire chest will be trained (including your “inner” chest). It’s just a matter of which area is emphasized. However, as someone who started off with a weak inner chest, I promise it will grow and look more developed as your entire chest develops.
-

node.text:
SKINNY FAT by @apfau
-
Are you skinny fat? First, let me define skinny fat as someone who is not overweight but has very little muscle mass and a decently high body fat percentage which results in looking skinny in clothes but not very lean without them.
-
If you are just starting out and haven’t taken advantage of your noob gains yet, I recommend eating in a slight caloric deficit while following a solid beginner program geared towards gaining strength. Due to beginner gains, you will actually be able to reduce fat while building muscle at the same time. When you are just starting out and haven’t trained before, you have a unique opportunity to gain muscle while losing fat and should take advantage of it. Most people who are skinny fat fit into this category.
-
If you have been lifting for a while, you really shouldn’t be skinny fat since you should have put on a decent amount of muscle at that point. You might just be fat and in that case, you should cut. However, some people are in an between stage and are unsure of what to do. You probably won’t be able to gain muscle while reducing fat at this stage so you need to decide which is more important to you. You can cut a bit first to get to a lower body fat percentage despite having minimal muscle and from there you can attempt to gain weight slowly while maintaining that level of leanness. Alternatively, if being lean isn’t a priority, you can go on a slow bulk and focus on adding muscle with the plan to cut down later.
-
Ultimately, it comes down to your personal comfort level with your body and your goals. No one can decide what to do for you and only you live with the decision. However, if you already feel uncomfortable with how much fat you’re carrying, it’s probably best to cut regardless of muscle mass or lack of it.

This video was taken 2 weeks out of the last bodybuilding competition I competed in back in 2015 when I won my pro card.
-
My least favorite part about competing in bodybuilding, besides the fake tan, was posing practice. I always enjoyed the training. I never minded the strict diet. I tolerated the cardio. I did not like posing practice though.
-
I’m not entirely sure why. Perhaps it was partly because by the time I was done with my workouts and cardio, I was exhausted and just wanted to nap, not strip down to my underwear and start flexing. Although my posing did significantly improve between my first show and my last, posing was never one of my strengths and I guess most people don’t enjoy doing something they’re not good at.
-
Posing is a huge part of bodybuilding though. A few minor tweaks can make a drastic difference and be the deciding factor between winning and losing. Besides actually hitting the poses correctly, an overlooked aspect is conditioning. It’s not nearly as easy as it looks. In a competitive class, you can be on stage under the bright, hot lights for 20 minutes and the judges will have you doing 12-15 poses multiple times and holding each one for roughly 10 seconds. You’ll be out of breath. You’ll be sweating. Fake tan will be dripping. The fatigue causes the people who weren’t  prepared to run out of stamina by the end and they can’t hit their poses properly.
-
So, if you plan to compete, don’t overlook posing. It doesn’t make much sense to put in all the effort to look your best if you can’t present it properly.

-
If you’re intimidated by the gym, you’re definitely not alone. Most people experience gym anxiety to some extent at some point including myself when I first started.
-
Although a consistent, long term workout partner is harder to find than toilet paper at the beginning of a pandemic, going to the gym with a friend as a beginner will help you feel a lot less awkward even if both of you don’t really know what you’re doing. If you don’t have a partner, try listening to music to drown out the background noise and get in a zone.
-
If you’re intimidated because you feel like people are judging your physique, wear a hoodie or baggy clothes. I did this for years. If possible, you can also try to avoid peak gym times and go when it’s less crowded.
-
It’s amazing how much more confidence you’ll have when you have a solid plan. If you’re aimlessly wandering around the gym doing random exercises, you’re more likely to doubt yourself and feel insecure. If you know your plan is solid, you’ll be focused, motivated, and feel secure in what you’re doing.
-
Most importantly, realize that no one is actually judging you. Anyone who is confident in themselves and what they’re doing probably doesn’t even notice you. Anyone who does notice you is probably looking at you because they’re just as insecure as you and they are curious what other people are doing since they’re looking for ideas themselves.

FLAT BENCH PRESS by @apfau
-
Which exercise would you like to see next? Leave it in the comments below💪🏼.
-
One of the biggest mistakes people make when bench pressing without realizing it is flaring their elbows. It’s natural when trying to lift too much weight. Doing this repetitively will likely lead to shoulder pain. Visually, the difference between the incorrect one and correct one doesn’t look like much. When my elbows are flared, my arms are at roughly a 90 degree angle. When my elbows are tucked, it’s more of a 75 degree angle. It’s subtle yet significant. That slight difference will help you target your chest more effectively and keep your shoulders safer.
-
Further, since bench is the ultimate ego lift, as the weight gets heavier, the range of motion seems to get smaller. Slightly arch your back and then focus on using complete range of motion by bringing the bar down to about nipple height or slightly below and let the bar touch your chest at the bottom if you can safely. It’s not about how much weight is on the bar but how well you’re actually working your chest safely.

DUMBBELL WORKOUT by @apfau
-
If all you have is a set of dumbbells at home, you can still have an effective workout. This is a full body workout that only utilizes dumbbells. Depending on the weight of the dumbbells that you have access to, you may need to do higher reps in order for the exercises to be challenging. This is just one example and you could always incorporate some body weight exercises like pull-ups and push-ups as well. node.text:
FACE-PULLS by @apfau
-
Face-pulls are by far my favorite rear delt exercise. They are excellent not only for rear delt development but for shoulder health too. However, they're rarely performed correctly.
-
To put the majority of the emphasis on the rear delts, I like to set the pulley at around chest height. From there, focus on pulling straight towards your forehead and externally rotate your shoulders at the top. It should almost look like you're doing a back double bicep at the peak of the contraction. You can do them seated as well.
-
Overall, you need to remember that shoulders are a tiny muscle group and rear delts are just a small part of that tiny muscle group. There's no need to try to load up the weight. Focus on performing the movement correctly and let those rear delts grow 💪🏼.
-

DELOADS by @apfau
-
A deload is a period of time, usually a week, where you back off your volume and/or intensity at the gym. The purpose is to give your body a necessary physical and mental break after a period of intense training to prevent burnout and to ensure you make progress long term.
-
When? I suggest deloading every 6-12 weeks. Closer to 6 weeks if you’re following more of a strength based program and closer to 12 if you focus mostly on hyPERtrophy. If you’re a beginner, you can go longer, probably closer to 6 months. You should do it before you start to feel like you actually need it because at that point, a week might not be enough to recover.
-
How? There is no “wrong” way to deload. Don’t overthink it. The whole point is just to back off and let your body and mind recover. You can reduce your volume by doing less sets or workouts per week, reduce your intensity by doing less weight, a combination of both, or you can even take a complete week off. Personally, I do the same routine with the same sets/reps but I reduce the weight by about 30%.
-
You should deload whether bulking or cutting and can keep your diet the same. You can continue to do cardio but if you do HIIT, you might want to switch to lower intensity for the week. If you decide to drop cardio for the week, then you might want to reduce your calories a little to compensate.

BICEP BLAST by @apfau
-
The bicep has two heads (hence the prefix “bi”). The two heads are the long head and the short head. However, there is an additional muscle, the brachialis, which technically is not part of the bicep but contributes to the overall development of your biceps.
-
The short head is the inner part of the bicep. It can be targeted with preacher curls as well as a generally wider grip. The long head is the outside of the bicep and can be targeted with a narrower grip as well as incline dumbbell curls, cable curls, and barbell curls.
-
The brachialis is a distinct muscle from your bicep. It sits somewhere between the bicep and the tricep. However, it will contribute to overall arm thickness and make your biceps appear larger since it pushes up against your bicep. Hammers curls are a good exercise to hit it.
-
Swipe left to see a photo of the first listed exercise from each column 💪🏼.

BUDGET BULKING by @apfau
-
Eating to gain muscle can be expensive. As you continue to gain size, your caloric needs will increase which means more food is required and more money spent on groceries. While it’s easy to spend a lot of money on food, there are also plenty of relatively inexpensive options as well.
-
Carbs are usually the least expensive while protein is the most expensive. Potatoes, oats, rice, and bananas are all pretty cheap especially if you buy in bulk (besides the bananas...don’t buy those in bulk). Although there are some expensive brands of chicken breast, it can be found relatively cheaply if you look for deals and buy in bulk. Tuna and eggs are always inexpensive and you can wait for a sale on whey protein that can last for months. For fats, buying peanut butter and nuts in larger quantities is usually the most affordable. If you can handle milk, it’s another inexpensive source of calories. Bulking can be expensive but it doesn’t have to be.
